properties.headline: Severe Thunderstorm Warning issued April 14 at 4:44PM EDT until April 14 at 5:15PM EDT by NWS Wilmington OH
properties.description:
At 443 PM EDT, a severe thunderstorm was located over Silver Grove,
moving northeast at 60 mph.

HAZARD...70 mph wind gusts.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Expect considerable tree damage. Damage is likely to mobile
homes, roofs, and outbuildings.

Locations impacted include...
Cincinnati, Covington, Mason, Fort Thomas, Newport, Blue Ash,
Loveland, Montgomery, Madeira, Alexandria, Highland Heights, Milford,
Taylor Mill, Deer Park, Dayton, Southgate, Forestville, Claryville,
Amelia and Mariemont.

This includes I-71 in Ohio between mile markers 10 and 15, and
between mile markers 18 and 24.
properties.instruction:
For your protection move to an interior room on the lowest floor of a
building.

To report severe weather, go to our website at weather.gov/iln and
submit your report via social media, when you can do so safely.

properties.headline: Wind Advisory issued April 14 at 4:43PM EDT until April 16 at 8:00AM EDT by NWS Boston/Norton MA
properties.description:
* WINDS...West 15 to 20 mph with gusts up to 50 mph.

* TIMING...The strongest winds will occur Monday evening into
Monday night.

* IMPACTS...Strong winds may blow down limbs, trees, and power
lines. Scattered power outages are possible.

* LOCATION...Most of Massachusetts near and north of the Mass
Pike.
properties.instruction:
A Wind Advisory means that sustained winds of 31 to 39 mph are
expected, with gusts between 46 to 57 mph. Winds this strong are
capable of downing small tree limbs and branches, possibly
causing isolated power outages. Driving can also be difficult,
especially for high profile vehicles. Use extra caution.

properties.headline: Tornado Warning issued April 14 at 4:41PM EDT until April 14 at 5:00PM EDT by NWS Cleveland OH
properties.description:
At 440 PM EDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing a tornado
was located over Crestline, or 11 miles east of Bucyrus, moving
northeast at 50 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado and half dollar size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed. Damage
to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree damage is
likely.

Locations impacted include...
Crestline, New Washington, Tiro and Sulpher Springs.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to a basement or an interior room on the lowest
floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

If a tornado or other severe weather is spotted, report it to the
National Weather Service or your local nearest law enforcement agency
who will send your report. This act may save lives of others in the
path of dangerous weather.

properties.description:

* TIMING...Overnight Sunday night into early Monday morning.

* IMPACTS...Frost could harm sensitive outdoor vegetation.
properties.instruction:

with agricultural interests in the Advisory area should protect
tender vegetation. Also, potted plants normally left outdoors
should be covered or brought inside away from the cold.

properties.description:

30s. Valleys and outlying areas may briefly drop below
freezing, especially in southern Illinois and southeast
Missouri.

* IMPACTS...Scattered to widespread frost is expected to develop
overnight and last through early Monday morning. This may damage
or kill tender young blooms and early season vegetation if
protective measures are not taken. Bring out door plants indoors
or cover them with some type of protective layer.
properties.instruction:

Sensitive outdoor plants may be killed if left uncovered.

properties.headline: Gale Watch issued April 14 at 4:40PM EDT until April 16 at 5:00PM EDT by NWS Boston/Norton MA
properties.description:
* WINDS AND SEAS...West winds 20 to 30 kt with gusts up to 45 kt.
Seas 4 to 7 feet.
properties.instruction:
A Small Craft Advisory means that wind speeds of 25 to 33 knots,
or seas 5 feet or greater, are expected to produce hazardous wave
conditions to small craft. Inexperienced mariners, especially
those operating smaller vessels, should avoid navigating in these
conditions.

A Gale Watch is issued when the risk of gale force winds of 34 to
47 knots has significantly increased...but the specific timing
and/or location is still uncertain. It is intended to provide
additional lead time for mariners who may wish to consider
altering their plans.

properties.areaDesc: Wilkes, NC
properties.headline: Tornado Warning issued April 14 at 4:39PM EDT until April 14 at 5:00PM EDT by NWS Blacksburg VA
properties.description:
At 439 PM EDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing a tornado
was located over Wilkesboro, moving northeast at 55 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed. Damage
to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree damage is
likely.

Locations impacted include...
North Wilkesboro...
Wilkesboro...
Ronda...
Mulberry...
and Buck.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to a basement or an interior room on the lowest
floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

Heavy rainfall may hide this tornado. Do not wait to see or hear the
tornado. TAKE COVER NOW!

When it is safe to do so, please send your reports of hail of any
size, as well as reports of any wind damage, including downed trees
or large limbs, to the National Weather Service by calling toll free
at 1...8 6 6...2 1 5...4 3 2 4. Reports and pictures can also be
shared on the National Weather Service Blacksburg Facebook page and
on Twitter.

properties.description:
Paint Rock River NEAR Woodville affecting Jackson...Madison and
Marshall Counties
The Flood Warning continues for
the Paint Rock River NEAR Woodville.
* until Tuesday evening.
* At 3 PM Sunday the stage was 13.4 feet and rising.
* Flood Stage is 15.0 feet.
* Minor Flooding is forecast.
* Forecast...Rise above Flood Stage by midnight tonight and
crest near 16.5 FEET BY early tomorrow evening. The river will fall
below Flood Stage by early Tuesday afternoon.
* Impact...At 16.0 feet...Flood waters affect mostly bottomland along
the river...including low lying farm and pasturelands.
* Flood history...This crest compares to a previous crest of 16.3 feet
on Feb 20 2019.
properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

Safety message...Do not attempt to drive through a flooded road. The
depth of water is not always obvious. As little as two feet of water
will carry most cars away. Also, the road bed may be washed out under
the water, and you could be stranded or trapped. Additional
information is available at http://water.weather.gov. Once there,
click on the Tennessee Valley to view local river information.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed. Damage
to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree damage is
likely.

properties.instruction:

floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

If a tornado or other severe weather is spotted, report it to the
National Weather Service or your local nearest law enforcement agency
who will send your report. This act may save lives of others in the
path of dangerous weather.

lower 30s over southeast Illinois on Monday morning. As a
result, widespread front will be possible over the region.

midnight tonight, and last through the early morning hours.

vegetation if protective measures are not taken.

properties.headline: Lakeshore Flood Warning issued April 14 at 4:10PM EDT until April 14 at 10:00PM EDT by NWS Cleveland OH
properties.description:
* LAKE SHORE FLOODING...Northeast winds of 20 to 30 knots will
cause higher than normal water levels on the western basin of
Lake Erie. Water levels were near 80 inches above low water
datum and had started to drop. This will result in minor
flooding and shoreline erosion along the lakeshore. Shifting
winds will allow levels to continue dropping into the evening
and levels will likely drop below 60 inches by 10pm.


* TIMING...Through this evening.

* IMPACTS...Flooding along the immediate lakeshore and beach and
shoreline erosion may be possible. Rising water levels in
marinas and waterways into the lake could submerge docks and
shoreline structures.
properties.instruction:
A Lakeshore Flood Warning is issued when flooding is occurring or
imminent along the lake. Residents on or near the shore in the
warned area should take immediate action to protect life and
property.

properties.description: The Gale Watch has been replaced. Please see the latest information from NWS Upton NY on this developing situation.
properties.instruction:
A Gale Warning means sustained winds or frequent gusts of 34 to
47 kt are expected or occurring. Operating a vessel in gale
conditions requires experience and properly equipped vessels. It
is highly recommended that mariners without the proper experience
seek safe harbor prior to the onset of gale conditions.

A Dense Fog Advisory means visibilities will frequently be
reduced to less than one mile. Inexperienced mariners, especially
those operating smaller vessels should avoid navigating in these
conditions.

A Small Craft Advisory means that sustained wind speeds or
frequent gusts of 25 to 33 kt and/or seas of 5 ft or higher are
expected or occurring, and hazardous to small craft.
Inexperienced mariners, especially those operating smaller
vessels, should avoid navigating in these conditions.

properties.instruction:
A Gale Warning means sustained winds or frequent gusts of 34 to
47 kt are expected or occurring. Operating a vessel in gale
conditions requires experience and properly equipped vessels. It
is highly recommended that mariners without the proper experience
seek safe harbor prior to the onset of gale conditions.

A Dense Fog Advisory means visibilities will frequently be
reduced to less than one mile. Inexperienced mariners, especially
those operating smaller vessels should avoid navigating in these
conditions.

A Small Craft Advisory means that sustained wind speeds or
frequent gusts of 25 to 33 kt and/or seas of 5 ft or higher are
expected or occurring, and hazardous to small craft.
Inexperienced mariners, especially those operating smaller
vessels, should avoid navigating in these conditions.

properties.headline: Winter Weather Advisory issued April 14 at 3:54PM EDT until April 15 at 4:00AM EDT by NWS Detroit/Pontiac MI
properties.description:
* WHAT...Occasional snow is expected to persist through this
evening. Pockets of heavy snow will be possible at times. Snow
will continue at times into tonight. Total snow accumulations of
2 to 5 inches expected. The highest snow totals will occur in
and around Sanford and Coleman. Northeast winds will gust as
high as 35 to 40 mph.

* WHERE...Midland, Bay and Saginaw Counties.

* WHEN...Through 4 AM EDT Monday.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Accumulations will be greatest on grassy
surfaces. However, plan on slippery road conditions at times
as periods of heavier snow will lead to some accumulations on
area roadways. Reduced visibilities can also be expected from
the snowfall.
properties.instruction:
A Winter Weather Advisory for snow means periods of snow will
cause primarily travel difficulties. Expect snow covered roads
and limited visibilities, and use caution while driving.

hashtag nwsgsp. Your message should describe the event and the

properties.headline: Tornado Warning issued April 14 at 3:49PM EDT until April 14 at 4:00PM EDT by NWS Greenville-Spartanburg SC
properties.description:
At 349 PM EDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing a tornado
was located 4 miles south of Morganton, or 4 miles southeast of Glen
Alpine, moving northeast at 50 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed. Damage
to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree damage is
likely.

This dangerous storm will be near...
Glen Alpine around 350 PM EDT.
Morganton, Drexel, Valdese, Rutherford College and Connelly
Springs around 400 PM EDT.

Other locations impacted by this dangerous storm include Oak Hill.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to a basement or an interior room on the lowest
floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

Please report damaging winds, hail, or flooding to the National
Weather Service Greenville-Spartanburg by calling toll free, 1, 800,
2 6 7, 8 1 0 1, or by posting on our Facebook page, or Tweet it using
hashtag nwsgsp. Your message should describe the event and the
specific location where it occurred.

The Flood Warning continues for
the Little Tallahatchie Canal at Etta near New Albany
* until Monday April 15.
* At 2 PM Sunday the stage was 25.3 feet.
* Minor flooding is occurring AND Minor flooding is forecast.
* Maximum forecast stage of 26.0 feet on Sunday April 14.
* Flood stage is 25.0 feet.
* The river rose above flood stage Sunday April 14 and will continue
rising to near 26.0 feet by Sunday April 14. The river will fall
below flood stage Monday April 15.

land are flooded.
properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

For graphical river and flood information...please go to
www.weather.gov and click near Memphis on the map, then select Rivers
and Lakes.

Do not drive through flooded areas...turn around don't drown.

Stay tuned to your weather radio and your local news media for the
latest river information.

properties.description:
Mississippi River at New Madrid affecting Fulton...Mississippi and
New Madrid Counties

.Runoff from heavy rainfall over the last 24 hours will cause the
Mississippi River at New Madrid to rise into minor flood stage. The
river is forecast to reach flood stage Wednesday morning and crest
near 34.9 feet Thursday.
The National Weather Service in Paducah, Kentucky has issued a

* Flood Warning for
the Mississippi River at New Madrid.
* from late Tuesday night to Tuesday April 23.
* At  2:00 PM Sunday the stage was 32.2 feet.
* Flood Stage is 34.0 feet.
* Minor flooding is forecast.
* Forecast...Rise above flood stage by Wednesday morning and continue
to rise to near 34.9 feet by Thursday evening. the river will fall
below flood stage by Tuesday, April 23.
* Impact...At 34.0 Feet...Minor flooding occurs affecting mainly
bottomland and surrounding low lying areas.
properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

SAFETY MESSAGE...

Never drive cars...trucks or sport utility vehicles through flooded
areas. The water may be too deep to allow safe passage. Never allow
children to play in or near flood waters. Stay tuned to NOAA Weather
Radio or your local media for further statements and possible updated
forecasts.

Additional information is available at
http://www.crh.noaa.gov/ahps2/index.php?wfo=pah /lower case/

properties.headline: Flood Watch issued April 14 at 3:35PM EDT until April 16 at 8:00AM EDT by NWS Burlington VT
properties.description:
The Flood Watch continues for

* All of Vermont excluding Grand Isle, and Franklin, Clinton,
Essex, and St. Lawrence counties in Northern New York.

* From 11 PM EDT this evening through Tuesday morning.

* Abnormally warm temperatures on Saturday produced significant
snow melt bringing rivers close to bank full early Sunday
morning. A moisture- laden frontal system will bring widespread
rainfall this evening through Monday morning with rainfall
amounts from 0.75 to 1.25 inches expected. The combination of
rain and snow melt will potentially cause main stem river
flooding on the Ausable, Missisquoi, Passumpsic, Otter Creek,
Winooski, Lamoille, and possibly the Mad river. Sharp river
rises are likely beginning tonight. Most main stem rivers are
expected to crest during the day Monday based on current
indications.

* Those with interests in low-lying or flood prone areas should
continue to monitor the latest forecasts over the weekend and
into Monday.
properties.instruction:
A Flood Watch means there is a potential for flooding based on
current forecasts.

You should monitor later forecasts and be alert for possible
Flood Warnings. Those living in areas prone to flooding should be
prepared to take action should flooding develop.

properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Greenville-Spartanburg has issued a

* Severe Thunderstorm Warning for...
Eastern McDowell County in western North Carolina...
Northeastern Rutherford County in western North Carolina...
Southwestern Caldwell County in western North Carolina...
Northwestern Cleveland County in the Piedmont of North Carolina...
Burke County in western North Carolina...

* Until 415 PM EDT.

* At 331 PM EDT, a severe thunderstorm was located 8 miles southeast
of Marion, moving northeast at 45 mph.

HAZARD...60 mph wind gusts.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Expect damage to trees and power lines.

* Locations impacted include...
Morganton, Marion, Drexel, Glen Alpine, Lake James State Park,
Table Rock, South Mountains State Park, Lake James, Nebo and
Thermal City.
properties.instruction:
Remain alert for a possible tornado! Tornadoes can develop quickly
from severe thunderstorms. If you spot a tornado go at once into the
basement or small central room in a sturdy structure.

Scattered trees and power lines will be blown down in the warned
area. Seek shelter inside an interior room.

Please report damaging winds, hail, or flooding to the National
Weather Service Greenville-Spartanburg by calling toll free, 1, 800,
2 6 7, 8 1 0 1, or by posting on our Facebook page, or Tweet it using
hashtag nwsgsp. Your message should describe the event and the
specific location where it occurred.

properties.headline: Lakeshore Flood Warning issued April 14 at 3:27PM EDT until April 14 at 9:00PM EDT by NWS Detroit/Pontiac MI
properties.description:
* Lakeshore Flooding...Sustained east northeast wind near 30 mph
with higher gusts will continue through late afternoon along the
western shoreline of Lake Erie. Although wind speed will begin
to diminish after 4 PM, continued onshore flow from the
northeast will support an ongoing flooding threat, especially
from Luna Pier to Maumee Bay. Winds will decrease and veer to
the north this evening, which will allow the lake levels to
decrease.

* Impacts...The combination of high water and wave action will
support flooding along the coast line and beach erosion.
properties.instruction:

imminent along the lake. Residents on or near the shore in the
warned area should be alert for rising water...and take
appropriate action to protect life and property.

Flood Warnings. Those living in areas prone to flooding should be
prepared to take action should flooding develop.

properties.headline: Severe Thunderstorm Warning issued April 14 at 3:18PM EDT until April 14 at 3:45PM EDT by NWS Peachtree City GA
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Peachtree City has issued a

* Severe Thunderstorm Warning for...
Northern Laurens County in central Georgia...

* Until 345 PM EDT.

* At 317 PM EDT, a severe thunderstorm was located near Dexter, or 10
miles southwest of Dublin, moving northeast at 35 mph.

HAZARD...60 mph wind gusts and an enhanced risk of a tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Expect damage to roofs, siding, and trees.

* Locations impacted include...
Dublin, East Dublin, Dexter, Dudley, Lovett, Harlow, Tuckers
Crossroad and Brewton.
properties.instruction:
A Tornado Watch remains in effect until 700 PM EDT for central and
east central Georgia.

Remain alert for a possible tornado! Tornadoes can develop quickly
from severe thunderstorms. If you spot a tornado go at once into the
basement or small central room in a sturdy structure.

For your protection move to an interior room on the lowest floor of a
building.

If you see wind damage...hail or flooding...wait until the storm has
passed...and then call the National Weather Service toll free
at 1 8 6 6 7 6 3 4 4 6 6 or tweet us your report at NWSATLANTA.

properties.headline: Flood Advisory issued April 14 at 3:17PM EDT until April 14 at 9:15PM EDT by NWS Blacksburg VA
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in BLACKSBURG has issued a

* Flood Advisory for...
Central Surry County in northwestern North Carolina...
Northeastern Wilkes County in northwestern North Carolina...
Southwestern Floyd County in southwestern Virginia...
Southeastern Carroll County in southwestern Virginia...
Western Patrick County in southwestern Virginia...

* Until 915 PM EDT

* At 315 PM EDT, Doppler radar indicated continued heavy rain due to
thunderstorms. This will cause minor flooding in the advisory area.
Up to two inches of rain have already fallen.

* Some locations that will experience flooding include...
Mount Airy...
Elkin...
Flat Rock...
Dobson...
and Ronda.

Additional rainfall of up to 1 inch is expected over the area. This
additional rain will result in minor flooding.
properties.instruction:
Excessive runoff from heavy rainfall will cause flooding of small
creeks and streams, country roads, farmland, and other low lying
spots.

When it is safe to do so, please send your reports of flooding,
including mudslides or flooded roads, to the National Weather Service
by calling toll free at 1...8 6 6...2 1 5...4 3 2 4. Reports and
pictures can also be shared on the National Weather Service
Blacksburg Facebook page and on Twitter.

properties.description:

was located near Tremont City, moving northeast at 40 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed. Damage
to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree damage is
likely.

Locations impacted include...
Springfield, Urbana, Tremont City, Mutual, Cable, Westville,
Lippincott, Powhattan, Mingo, Catawba Station, Kennard, Terre Haute
and Lawrenceville.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to a basement or an interior room on the lowest
floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

To report severe weather, go to our website at weather.gov/iln and
submit your report via social media, when you can do so safely.

properties.areaDesc: Coastal Bay; Coastal Gulf; South Walton
properties.headline: Rip Current Statement issued April 14 at 3:06PM EDT until April 15 at 4:00AM EDT by NWS Tallahassee FL
properties.description:
* WAVES AND SURF...Surf height 5 to 8 feet. High risk of rip
currents continues through late tonight.

* Timing...Through late tonight.

There is a high risk of rip currents.

Rip currents are powerful channels of water flowing quickly away
from shore, which occur most often at low spots or breaks in the
sandbar and in the vicinity of structures such as groins, jetties
and piers. Heed the advice of lifeguards, beach patrol flags and
signs.

If you become caught in a rip current, yell for help. Remain
calm, do not exhaust yourself and stay afloat while waiting for
help. If you have to swim out of a rip current, swim parallel to
shore and back toward the beach when possible. Do not attempt to
swim directly against a rip current as you will tire quickly.

A High Surf Advisory means that high surf will affect beaches in
the advisory area, producing localized beach erosion and
dangerous swimming conditions.

properties.areaDesc: Wabash, IL; Daviess, IN; Knox, IN; Gibson, IN; Pike, IN
properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 14 at 2:48PM EDT until April 22 at 6:30PM EDT by NWS Indianapolis IN
properties.description:
Mississinewa River...Wabash River...White River...


.Lowland flooding began on the Wabash River late this Sunday
morning at Riverton in southwest Indiana.  Lowland flooding will
develop this week along much of the rest of the river as well as on
the White River south of Indianapolis.  Brief flooding on
the Mississinewa in the vicinity of Ridgeville is
expected today.  Smaller rivers and creeks may also go
into flood briefly through Sunday night.  Significant flooding is
not expected on any central and southern Indiana area rivers.

Rainfall from two separate storm systems is the cause of the
flooding.  System number one was this past Thursday night and
Friday morning with up to 1.75 inches, heaviest from southwestern
Indiana to north central Indiana.  System two, currently moving
through, brought as much as 1.70 inches of rain through 1 PM EDT,
heaviest from southwest Indiana to the Indianapolis area.  Up to
three tenths of an inch more of rain is expected between 1 PM and
when it ends Sunday evening.

Dry weather is forecast for Monday and Tuesday, a negligible amount
of rain Wednesday morning, then potentially substantial rainfall
Wednesday night through Thursday night and lighter amounts
continuing into Friday night.
The Flood Warning continues for

properties.areaDesc: Vermillion, IN; Warren, IN; Fountain, IN; Tippecanoe, IN; Parke, IN
properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 14 at 2:48PM EDT until April 17 at 6:48PM EDT by NWS Indianapolis IN
properties.description:
Mississinewa River...Wabash River...White River...


.Lowland flooding began on the Wabash River late this Sunday
morning at Riverton in southwest Indiana.  Lowland flooding will
develop this week along much of the rest of the river as well as on
the White River south of Indianapolis.  Brief flooding on
the Mississinewa in the vicinity of Ridgeville is
expected today.  Smaller rivers and creeks may also go
into flood briefly through Sunday night.  Significant flooding is
not expected on any central and southern Indiana area rivers.

Rainfall from two separate storm systems is the cause of the
flooding.  System number one was this past Thursday night and
Friday morning with up to 1.75 inches, heaviest from southwestern
Indiana to north central Indiana.  System two, currently moving
through, brought as much as 1.70 inches of rain through 1 PM EDT,
heaviest from southwest Indiana to the Indianapolis area.  Up to
three tenths of an inch more of rain is expected between 1 PM and
when it ends Sunday evening.

Dry weather is forecast for Monday and Tuesday, a negligible amount
of rain Wednesday morning, then potentially substantial rainfall
Wednesday night through Thursday night and lighter amounts
continuing into Friday night.
The Flood Warning continues for
The Wabash River at Lafayette.
* from Monday afternoon to Wednesday evening.
* At  1:30 PM Sunday the stage was 7.1 feet.
* Flood stage is 11.0 feet.
* Minor flooding is forecast.
* Forecast...Rise above flood stage by Monday afternoon and continue
to rise to near 12.2 feet by Tuesday morning.  It will fall below
flood stage by Wednesday morning.
* At 12.0 feet...High water affects a few low river cabins and county
roads.
properties.instruction:
Precautionary/Preparedness Actions...

Motorists should never drive into flood water. Turn around and go
another way. Keep children away from flooded areas. Recreational and
agricultural interests should remain alert to changing river
conditions.

For detailed flood information go to weather.gov/ind on the web and
click on rivers and lakes.

If you live or travel near streams and rivers seek higher ground
immediately at first signs of rising water. Obey all road closure

around, don't drown!

Stay tuned to developments by listening to noaa weather radio, or by
visiting our web site at: weather.gov.

properties.headline: Winter Weather Advisory issued April 14 at 11:44AM PDT until April 16 at 11:00AM PDT by NWS Sacramento CA
properties.description:
A storm system will move through NorCal Monday into early
Tuesday. Snow is expected to begin over the Sierra during the
late morning hours Monday and increase in intensity during the
afternoon. Snow will diminish Tuesday morning.
* WHAT...Snow expected. Plan on difficult travel conditions,
including during the afternoon commute on Monday. Total snow
accumulations of 6 to 10 inches, with localized amounts over a
foot, are expected.

* WHERE...Western Plumas County/Lassen Park and West Slope
Northern Sierra Nevada including Interstate 80 over Donner
Pass, Highway 50 over Echo Summit and Highway 88 over Carson
Pass.

* WHEN...11 AM Monday to 11 AM Tuesday.

* ADDITIONAL DETAILS...Be prepared for reduced visibilities at
times.
properties.instruction:
A Winter Weather Advisory for snow means periods of snow will
cause primarily travel difficulties. Be prepared for snow covered
roads and limited visibilities, and use caution while driving.
The latest road conditions for the state you are calling from can
be obtained by calling 5 1 1.

properties.headline: Flood Warning issued April 14 at 2:35PM EDT until April 15 at 10:54AM EDT by NWS Indianapolis IN
properties.description:
Mississinewa River...

.Lowland flooding will be developing this Sunday afternoon in
the vicinity of Ridgeville on the Mississinewa River as a result
of rainfall overnight and during the day today.  Significant
flooding is not expected.

Rain will be coming to an end tonight followed by dry weather for a
couple days.  More rain later this week may bring a return to the
flooding.
The National Weather Service in Indianapolis has issued a

* Flood Warning for
the Mississinewa River near Ridgeville.
* until Monday morning.
* At 2:00 PM Sunday the stage was 10.0 feet.
* Flood stage is 10.0 feet.
* Minor flooding is forecast.
* Forecast...Rise above flood stage by this afternoon and continue to
rise to near 10.9 feet by this evening.  It will fall below flood
stage by late tonight.
* At 11.0 feet...Lowland agricultural flooding along CR 100 W just
north of the river.  High water affecting a small portion of River
Road just east of SR 1 and north of the river.  Water is within a
few feet vertically of the approaches to SR 1 bridge in western
Randolph county.
properties.instruction:
Precautionary/Preparedness Actions...

Motorists should never drive into flood water. Turn around and go
another way. Keep children away from flooded areas. Recreational and
agricultural interests should remain alert to changing river
conditions.

For detailed flood information go to weather.gov/ind on the web and
click on rivers and lakes.

evening. The highest winds will impact the mountains, but strong
winds will also affect the Cumberland Plateau and Great Valley
through the afternoon. Winds will diminish this evening.

gusts of 58 mph or stronger can be expected at times.  Winds of
these magnitudes can cause property damage and power outages.

vehicles.

properties.headline: Severe Thunderstorm Warning issued April 14 at 2:20PM EDT until April 14 at 2:45PM EDT by NWS Greenville-Spartanburg SC
properties.description:
At 220 PM EDT, a severe thunderstorm was located 7 miles south of
Pickens, or near Norris, moving northeast at 45 mph.

HAZARD...60 mph wind gusts and quarter size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Minor hail damage to vehicles is expected. Expect wind
damage to trees and power lines.

Locations impacted include...
Easley, Pickens, Central, Liberty, Norris, Six Mile, Rosman, Jocassee
Gorges, Dupont State Forest and Table Rock State Park.
properties.instruction:
Remain alert for a possible tornado! Tornadoes can develop quickly
from severe thunderstorms. If you spot a tornado go at once into the
basement or small central room in a sturdy structure.

Scattered trees and power lines will be blown down in the warned
area. Seek shelter inside an interior room.

Please report damaging winds, hail, or flooding to the National
Weather Service Greenville-Spartanburg by calling toll free, 1, 800,
2 6 7, 8 1 0 1, or by posting on our Facebook page, or Tweet it using
hashtag nwsgsp. Your message should describe the event and the
specific location where it occurred.

properties.headline: Small Craft Advisory issued April 14 at 1:18PM CDT until April 14 at 1:00PM CDT by NWS Brownsville TX
properties.description:
A broad area of high pressure spreading over the western Gulf of
Mexico will maintain strong northerly surface winds and elevated
Gulf swells this afternoon.
The National Weather Service in Brownsville has issued a Small
Craft Advisory, which is in effect until 6 PM CDT this evening.

* WINDS...North winds 20 to 25 knots.

* WAVES/SEAS...5 to 7 feet nearshore. 6 to 8 feet offshore.
properties.instruction:
A Small Craft Advisory means that wind speeds of 20 to 33 knots
are expected to produce hazardous wave conditions to small craft.
Inexperienced mariners...especially those operating smaller
vessels should avoid navigating in these conditions.

properties.areaDesc: Ben Hill, GA
properties.headline: Tornado Warning issued April 14 at 2:17PM EDT until April 14 at 2:30PM EDT by NWS Tallahassee FL
properties.description:
At 217 PM EDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing a tornado
was located 7 miles north of Fitzgerald, moving northeast at 40 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed. Damage
to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree damage is
likely.

This tornadic thunderstorm will remain over mainly rural areas of
northwestern Ben Hill County, including the following locations...
Lulaville, Bowens Mill and Queensland.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to a basement or an interior room on the lowest
floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

properties.headline: Tornado Warning issued April 14 at 2:16PM EDT until April 14 at 2:15PM EDT by NWS Blacksburg VA
properties.description:
The storm which prompted the warning has weakened below severe
limits, and no longer appears capable of producing a tornado.
Therefore, the warning has been allowed to expire.  However gusty
winds and heavy rain are still possible with this thunderstorm.

When it is safe to do so, please send your reports of hail of any
size, as well as reports of any wind damage, including downed trees
or large limbs, to the National Weather Service by calling toll free
at 1...8 6 6...2 1 5...4 3 2 4. Reports and pictures can also be
shared on the National Weather Service Blacksburg Facebook page and
on Twitter.

show signs of broad rotation. A future tornado warning issuance may
be required if this rotation tightens any.

properties.instruction:

including extremely large hail, destructive straight line winds and
tornadoes. Move quickly to a safe shelter, such as an interior room,
a bathroom or closet or basement.

* At 151 PM EDT, a severe thunderstorm capable of producing a tornado
was located near Mountain Park, moving northeast at 45 mph.

HAZARD...Tornado.

SOURCE...Radar indicated rotation.

IMPACT...Flying debris will be dangerous to those caught without
shelter. Mobile homes will be damaged or destroyed.
Damage to roofs, windows, and vehicles will occur.  Tree
damage is likely.

* Locations impacted include...
Mount Airy...
Flat Rock...
Dobson...
Ararat...
and Cana.
properties.instruction:
TAKE COVER NOW! Move to a basement or an interior room on the lowest
floor of a sturdy building. Avoid windows. If you are outdoors, in a
mobile home, or in a vehicle, move to the closest substantial shelter
and protect yourself from flying debris.

properties.headline: Lakeshore Flood Warning issued April 14 at 1:49PM EDT until April 15 at 8:00PM EDT by NWS Detroit/Pontiac MI
properties.description:
The National Weather Service in Detroit/Pontiac has issued a
Lakeshore Flood Warning, which is in effect until 8 PM EDT
Monday. The Lakeshore Flood Advisory is no longer in effect.

* Lakeshore Flooding...Sustained east northeast wind near 30 mph
with higher gusts will continue through mid afternoon along the
western shoreline of Lake Erie. Although wind speed will begin
to diminish by 4 PM, continued onshore flow from the northeast
will support an ongoing flooding threat, especially from Luna
Pier to Maumee Bay.

* Impacts...At 130 PM water levels at Toledo, Fermi, and Gibraltar
were 82, 72, and 68 inches above chart datum respectively.
Additional rises will be possible through 4 PM before wind
begins to turn northerly and weaken. The greatest flooding
potential will be between Luna Pier and the Ohio border.
properties.instruction:
To learn more about dangerous waves and currents please visit
dangerouscurrents.org

A Lakeshore Flood Warning means that flooding is occurring or
imminent along the lake. Residents on or near the shore in the
warned area should be alert for rising water...and take
appropriate action to protect life and property.

* Prepare, plan and stay informed. Visit www.weather.gov/safety

NWSheadline: LAKESHORE FLOOD WARNING IN EFFECT UNTIL 8 PM EDT MONDAY

properties.description:
* Lakeshore Flooding...Northeast wind will continue to
strengthen today, peaking near 30 mph with gusts up to 40 mph
this evening. Wind will then switch gradually to the north
overnight and remain strong into Monday morning. These winds
will lead to very high waves as well as a general increase in
the lake water level.

* Impacts...The high waves and rising water level will lead to
significant beach erosion in some areas and localized
lakeshore flooding from this afternoon into tonight before
gradually improving on Monday morning.

properties.headline: Lakeshore Flood Warning issued April 14 at 1:49PM EDT until April 15 at 4:00AM EDT by NWS Detroit/Pontiac MI
properties.description:
* Lakeshore Flooding...Although water levels at Essexville have
plateaued in the short term, northeast winds up to 35 mph with
higher gusts are still forecast to develop and persist from 4 PM
through midnight. The persistent onshore flow and elevated
waves will result in flooding along the immediate lakeshore.


* Impacts...The water level at Essexville was 52 inches above
chart datum at 130 PM and is expected to begin steadily
increasing no later than 5 PM. The water level is then forecast
to exceed 60 inches during the evening with a low potential to
reach 70 inches before wind begins to weaken and turn northerly
after midnight. The increased water level, along with high wave
action, will result in flooding of the lakeshore and may damage
suceptible structures along the shoreline.

* Until 315 PM EDT/215 PM CDT/.

* At 148 PM EDT/1248 PM CDT/, severe thunderstorms capable of
producing waterspouts were located along a line extending from 8 nm
northwest of C Tower to 17 nm south of S Tower to 60 nm south of
Empire Mica Wreck, moving northeast at 40 knots.

HAZARD...Waterspouts and wind gusts to 40 knots.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Waterspouts can quickly form and capsize boats...damage
vessels...and create suddenly higher waves. Make sure all
on board are in a secure location and wearing life
jackets. Expect wind gusts in excess of 34
knots...suddenly higher waves...frequent lightning...and
heavy downpours. Make sure all on board are wearing life
jackets.

* Locations impacted include...
Buckeye Reef, O Tower, K Tower, S Tower, V Tower, Apalachicola, C
Tower, St George Island and Marker 24 Barge.
properties.instruction:
Move to safe harbor until hazardous weather passes.

Frequent lightning is occurring with these storms. If caught on the
open water stay below deck if possible, keep away from ungrounded
metal objects.

Northwestern Lee County in central North Carolina...
Southwestern Chatham County in central North Carolina...

* Until 230 PM EDT

* At 148 PM EDT, a severe thunderstorm was located 7 miles southeast
of Biscoe, or 12 miles east of Troy, moving northeast at 40 mph.

HAZARD...60 mph wind gusts and quarter size hail.

SOURCE...Radar indicated.

IMPACT...Hail damage to vehicles is expected. Expect wind damage
to roofs, siding, and trees.

* Locations impacted include...
Siler City, Goldston, Robbins, Seven Lakes, Cumnock, Harpers
Crossroads, Highfalls, Coleridge, Eagle Springs and Hasty.
properties.instruction:
Straight line winds can blow down trees, power lines, and damage
mobile homes and other buildings. Seek shelter in a sturdy structure
until the storm has passed. Stay away from windows as flying debris
generated by damaging winds can be deadly.

This thunderstorm is capable of producing all types of severe weather
including extremely large hail, destructive straight line winds and
tornadoes. Move quickly to a safe shelter such as an interior room, a
bathroom, closet or basement.

properties.instruction:

building.

Continuous cloud to ground lightning is occurring with these storms.
Move indoors immediately. Lightning is one of nature's leading
killers. Remember, if you can hear thunder, you are close enough to
be struck by lightning.

properties.headline: Flood Watch issued April 14 at 1:44PM EDT until April 17 at 2:00AM EDT by NWS Boston/Norton MA
properties.description:
Connecticut River At Montague affecting Franklin and Hampshire
Counties
Connecticut River At Northampton affecting Hampden and Hampshire
Counties
Connecticut River At Thompsonville affecting Hartford and Hampden
Counties
Connecticut River At Hartford affecting Hartford and Middlesex
Counties
Connecticut River At Middle Haddam affecting Middlesex County


Rainfall totals tonight into Monday could range from 0.75 to 1.25
inches. Warm temperatures over Northern New England this weekend will
result in snow melt of an existing snow pack. The combination of
rainfall tonight into Monday and snow melt could result in sharp rises
on the lower Connecticut River through Tuesday. The lower Connecticut
River is vulnerable to river gauges potentially reaching and exceeding
flood stage levels late Monday night around and after Midnight at
Montague and Northampton, then later Tuesday afternoon/evening at
Thompsonville, Hartford and Middle Haddam. Therefore a river flood
watch has been issued for the lower Connecticut River.
The National Weather Service in Boston/Norton, MA has issued a
* Flood Watch for
The Connecticut River At Thompsonville
* from Tuesday evening to late Tuesday night.
* At 12:30 PM Sunday the stage was 12.2 feet.
* Minor flooding is possible.
* Flood stage is 15.0 feet.
* Forecast...Flood stage may be reached by Tuesday evening.
* Impact...At 15.0 feet...Lowland flooding will begin along the
Connecticut River near Thompsonville.
properties.instruction:
PRECAUTIONARY/PREPAREDNESS ACTIONS...

Safety Message...Observed river stages are courtesy of the U.S.
Geological Survey and other cooperating agencies. Please stay tuned
to NOAA Weather Radio or your local television or radio stations for
the latest information on this river flood event.
